    }
}
No manual coordinate typing is required.

You drive there and press the button.

🚦 Race start system
A player chooses a race.

PinkiRaces shows:

race

player

current vehicle

distance from start

personal best

They can hit:

ROUTE TO START

The app uses TT's waypoint/blip system to route them there.

TT exposes setWaypoint, addBlip, setBlipRoute, numbered blips and related controls specifically for User Apps. 


Once they are inside the configured start radius:

ARM RACE

Then:

3
2
1
GO!
The timer begins precisely at GO using performance.now() rather than relying on a one-second clock.

I also added a false-start check.

If the vehicle moves more than 5 metres during the countdown, the run gets marked:

INVALID — False Start

It can still finish, but it will not become a valid leaderboard time.

📍 Checkpoints
Checkpoints must be completed in exact order.

Example:

Start → CP1 → CP2 → CP3 → CP4 → Finish

Driving directly from Start to CP4 does nothing.

PinkiRaces constantly compares:

player X/Y
vs.
current checkpoint X/Y
When the player enters that checkpoint's configured radius:

checkpoint completes

split time is recorded

sound plays

next checkpoint becomes active

GPS/blip advances

progress updates

The finish behaves as the final checkpoint.

One TT limitation I deliberately did not fake
The documented User Apps commands provide blips, routes, map waypoints and position data, but there is no documented command for spawning GTA-style physical 3D checkpoint cylinders/rings in the world. That conclusion comes from the available User App command interface. 


So right now PinkiRaces uses:

numbered/routed map checkpoint + physical proximity detection

The checkpoint itself is absolutely real from the race logic's perspective — you physically have to drive through its coordinate radius — but it isn't yet a floating GTA race ring.

We may be able to investigate another visual trick later.

🚗 Vehicle tracking
This uses exactly the sort of information your debugger exposed.

At race start it locks:

vehicle model
vehicle name
vehicle make
vehicle class
vehicle class name
For your example that would record something like:

Player: Prim
User ID: 757858

Model:
deluxo

Display:
Imponte Deluxo

Class:
Flying Cars
TT's documented data includes vehicle, vehicleClass, vehicleName, vehicleMake, and vehicleClassName. 


If someone begins in:

Elegy Retro Custom

and switches midway into:

Deluxo

the run gets marked invalid:

Vehicle changed during the run.

That prevents obvious vehicle-switch leaderboard abuse.

